Dr. Murdoek, the latest and best trans- lator of Mosheim, has delivered the following opinion, which will probably commend itself to the judgmcnt of all well informed and impartial readers.

“Itis a common opinion that the early Arminians, who fiourished before the Synod of Dort, were much purer and more sound than the later ones, who lived aud taught after that council 3 and that Arminius himself only rejected Calvin's doctrine of absolute decrees, and its ne- cessary consequences, while, in everything else, he agreed with the Reformer 3 but that his disciples, and especially Episcopius, boldly passed the limits which their master had wisely established, and went over to the camp of the Pelagians and Socinians. But it appears to me very clear, that Arminius himself revolved in his own mind, and taught to his disciples‚ that form of religion which his followers afterwards professed3 and that the latter, espe- cially Episcopius, only perfected what their master taught them, and casting off fear, explained it more clearly. I have as a witness, besides others of less authority, Ar- minius himself, who, in his will, drawn up a little before his death, explicitly declares· that his aim was to bring all sects of Christians, with the exception of the Papists, into one community and brotherhood.
